Thread

A thread is the smallest unit of execution inside a process.
It represents a single sequence of instructions that the CPU executes.

In simple words:
A thread is one path of execution of a program.

A process can have one or many threads.

You do NOT create a thread inside a processor. The processor is hardware. Threads are created inside a process by the program or OS.
The processor only executes them.

So the real question is:

When do we create multiple threads instead of using another processor?

Because adding processors is hardware, while creating threads is software and much cheaper.

1. When tasks can run in parallel

If a program has multiple independent tasks, threads allow them to run at the same time.

Example 1
A browser:

Thread 1 → loading webpage

Thread 2 → downloading images

Thread 3 → running JavaScript

All tasks can run simultaneously.

Example 2
Video editing software:

Thread 1 → rendering frames

Thread 2 → audio processing

Thread 3 → UI updates

Instead of waiting for one task to finish, threads handle them together.

2. When you want faster performance

Some tasks can be split into smaller pieces and processed in parallel.

Example 1
Searching a large dataset:

Thread 1 → search first half

Thread 2 → search second half

Example 2
Matrix multiplication:

Thread 1 → compute first rows

Thread 2 → compute remaining rows

Parallel threads reduce total time.




























